  <chapter*|Chap.1 Latin and Indo-European>

  <section*|Introduction>

  Alternative hypothesis to genetic relevance: <em|chance similarity>,
  <em|linguistic borrowing>, <em|linguistic convergence>.

  An example of ``ne med malos tatod"

  <subsection*|1.2 The IE language family>

  <subparagraph|Anatolian>

  <em|Hittite>, attested in the cuneiform script, the ancient Near East,
  dating from the 16th century BC. Palaic and Luwian attested in cuneiform,
  the latter also in hieroglyphic. Later in alphabetic scripts, including
  Lydian, Lycian and Carian.

  <subparagraph|Greek>

  Second earliest attested, in Linear B syllabary, 14th Century\ 

  <subparagraph|Indo-Iranian>

  Indic: 2000 BC in cuneiform, major early: hymns of the Rg-Veda.

  Iranian: Zarathrustra in the Avesta, around 1000 BC for the composition of
  the Gathas and several centuries earlier for the oldest Vedic hymns.

  Indo-Iranian, Greek and Anatolian are the three most important brances for
  the reconstruction of PIE.

  <subparagraph|Latin and the language of Italy>

  <em|Latino-Faliscan>: Faliscan 7th-6th century BC <em|Sabellian group>:
  Oscan and Umbrian, 6th century BC <em|Venetic>: 6th century BC <em|Messapic
  languages>: greater divergence

  <subparagraph|Celtic>

  Only Irish, Scots Gaelic, Welsh and Breton surviving.

  Earliest attestations around the beginning of the Christian era. Old Irish:
  7th century AD

  Subgroups: Goidelic, Brythonic, Celtiberian, Gaulish, Lepontic It's not
  sure whether a continental Celtic actually reflects any linguistic reality.

  <subparagraph|German>

  1000 BC, the first extensive text is the Gothic Bible translation

  Old English 8th century, Old HG, Old Saxon and Old Norse the following
  century

  <subparagraph|Armenian>

  5th century AD Bible

  <subparagraph|Slavic>

  9th century Bible

  <subparagraph|Baltic>

  Lithunian, Latvian and Old Prussian 14-16th centuries written

  <subparagraph|Albanian>

  attested in texts from the late Middle Ages to the early modern period

  <subsection*|1.3 Reconstructed PIE>

  Assumption: a single language was spoken at some point in time from which
  all the different IE varieties have evolved.

  The <strong|Comparative Method> operates through identification of sets of
  correspondence in languages which are known to be related, and forming of
  hypotheses to explain the correspondence.\ 

  It is more likely that the reconstructed items are diffusely arraved in
  time and space and acrosss the speaker population.

