  <subparagraph|Latin morphosyntactic developments from PIE>

  \ <strong|Ablaut(vowel gradation)> in PIE

  <\enumerate>
    <item>Quantative ablaut: shift of word-accent within paradigm with a
    concomitant loss of the unaccented vowel

    <item>Qualitative ablaut: vowel quality change within the same syllable
  </enumerate>

  *e / *o or *e/zero alternation

  The example of <em|melior>: how ablaut disappeared from PIE to Latin

  <subparagraph|Nominal Declensions>

  The confusion of instrumental and ablative, the overlap between <em|origin>
  of the ablative and <em|path> of the instrumental,denoted by the old
  ablative marker -e in the 3rd declension may originate from the old
  locative *-i

  Besides dual, PIE may have a separate ``collective", taking the ending of
  the neuter plural. e.g. locus, loca, alongside locus, loci adjective in
  concord with two conjoined inanimate nouns of differing gender is inflected
